          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Types, Stages, Recognition, and Treatment\nLocation: Grand Teton National Park, Wyoming",
              "orderIndex": 0,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sectionTitle": "Types of Shock",
          "subtitle": null,
          "orderIndex": 1,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Normal",
              "orderIndex": 0,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Fluid level, pump & container are normal. HR: 60-100 bpm, RR: 12-24 bpm, BP: Normal (strong radial pulses), SCTM: Pink, warm & dry (PWD).",
              "orderIndex": 1,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Hypovolemic Shock",
              "orderIndex": 2,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Fluid problem, severe bleed or severe dehydration. Visual: Healthy red heart connected to red circular container, but blue liquid level significantly reduced (<4 liters). HR: Over 100 bpm, RR: Over 24 bpm, BP: Normal to low, SCTM: Pale, cool & clammy (PCC).",
              "orderIndex": 3,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Cardiogenic Shock",
              "orderIndex": 4,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Pump problem: MI, CHF or cardiac tamponade. Visual: Red heart with diagonal line through it (indicating problem), connected to red circular container completely filled with blue liquid (5 liters). HR: Over 100 bpm, RR: Over 24 bpm, BP: Normal to low, SCTM: Pale, cool & clammy (PCC). Diaphoresis (sweating profusely) is common.",
              "orderIndex": 5,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Anaphylactic Shock (Vasogenic)",
              "orderIndex": 6,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Container problem, severe allergy. HR: Over 100 bpm, RR: Over 24 bpm (wheezing), BP: Low, SCTM: Red, hot & sweaty (RHS). Swallowing and breathing difficulties are common. Abdominal pain, cramps, vomiting, diarrhea, hives, and angioedema (swelling similar to hives, but beneath the skin instead of on the surface) is also possible.",
              "orderIndex": 7,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Septic Shock (Vasogenic)",
              "orderIndex": 8,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Container problem, severe infection. HR: Over 100 bpm, RR: Over 24 bpm, BP: Low, SCTM: Red & hot. A fever is usually present.",
              "orderIndex": 9,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Neurogenic Shock (Vasogenic)",
              "orderIndex": 10,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Container problem, high cord injury (C1-T4). HR: Over 100 bpm (or below 60/min bradycardia in some cases depending on spinal cord injury), RR: Over 24 bpm or absent, BP: Low, SCTM: Red, hot & dry (RHD), CSM: Poor (especially sensory and motor). Neck and/or back pain is usually present if patient is conscious.",
              "orderIndex": 11,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sectionTitle": "Stages of Shock",
          "subtitle": null,
          "orderIndex": 2,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Compensatory Shock",
              "orderIndex": 0,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Signs/Symptoms:",
              "orderIndex": 1,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "bulletList",
              "content": "Approximately 1 liter of blood loss\nAVPU: Anxious, restless, & confused\nSCTM: Pale, cool, clammy, & diaphoretic\nHR: Tachycardia (above 100 bpm)\nRR: Tachypnea (above 24 bpm)\nBP: Strong radial pulse\nPERRL: Normal",
              "orderIndex": 2,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Decompensatory Shock",
              "orderIndex": 3,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Signs/Symptoms:",
              "orderIndex": 4,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "bulletList",
              "content": "Approximately 2 liters of blood loss\nAVPU: Drops to unresponsiveness\nSCTM: Very pale, cool, & clammy\nHR: Increased tachycardia (weak & thready)\nRR: Increased tachypnea (rapid & shallow)\nBP: No radial pulse bilaterally\nPERRL: Pupils are slow to react",
              "orderIndex": 5,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Irreversible Shock",
              "orderIndex": 6,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Signs/Symptoms:",
              "orderIndex": 7,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "bulletList",
              "content": "Over 2 liters of blood loss\nAVPU: Unresponsive\nSCTM: Cold & mottled\nHR: Extreme tachycardia (weak & thready)\nRR: Extreme tachypnea (rapid & shallow)\nBP: Weak to no palpable carotid pulses\nPERRL: Fixed & dilated",
              "orderIndex": 8,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "sectionTitle": "Treatment",
          "subtitle": null,
          "orderIndex": 3,
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": "Tx (Treatment):",
              "orderIndex": 0,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "bulletList",
              "content": "Assess ABCs\nStop blood loss\nAnticipate shock\nKeep patient calm & warm\nIV therapy if available\nHigh flow O\u2082 if available\nEvacuate immediately",
              "orderIndex": 1,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            },
            {
              "type": "warning",
              "content": "NOTE: Individuals who take beta-blockers or calcium channel blockers for high BP or arrhythmias may decompensate more rapidly with shock since these drugs block the heart from beating above 100 bpm. Beta-blockers end in \"olol\" (e.g., metoprolol, atenolol & propranolol). Calcium channel blockers end in \"dipine\" (e.g., amlodipine, nicardipine & felodipine).",
              "orderIndex": 2,
              "metadata": null,
              "location": null
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
